                            <comment id="13940423" author="martinkl" created="Wed, 19 Mar 2014 12:12:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think you&apos;re right &amp;#8211; all implementations, not just Java, should allow the name of any named type (record, enum, fixed) as type of a field. So this looks like a bug in the spec.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In addition, a field can be of a primitive type, or a union. So the most accurate would probably be to say that the type of a field can be any &lt;a href=&quot;http://avro.apache.org/docs/1.7.6/spec.html#schemas&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;schema declaration&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13940491" author="busbey" created="Wed, 19 Mar 2014 14:13:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;That&apos;s covered already in the &quot;A JSON object defining a schema&quot; clause, no?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13940562" author="martinkl" created="Wed, 19 Mar 2014 15:22:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I read &quot;a JSON object&quot; as referring to the thing with curly braces, whereas a union is represented as a JSON array, and a primitive type or a reference to a named type is represented as a JSON string. But I think we&apos;re saying the same thing. Do you want to submit a patch with better wording?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13940660" author="cutting" created="Wed, 19 Mar 2014 16:51:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is a bug in the specification.  It should really just say, &quot;a schema, as defined above&quot; or somesuch.  That current specification does not even permit unions, since they&apos;re JSON arrays, not objects or strings.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16066080" author="nkollar" created="Wed, 28 Jun 2017 07:49:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=busbey&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;busbey&quot;&gt;Sean Busbey&lt;/a&gt; modified the doc according to Doug&apos;s comment, could you please review the patch?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
